Confirmed the CI picture: `test.yml` builds + tests with `-mod=vendor` (vendor is checked in), gofmt **excludes** `vendor/`, and there's **no** `go mod vendor`/`go mod verify` re-sync check. That matters for one of the options below.

Short answer: **yes, you can keep it to this PR — but the bug genuinely belongs to git-sync, so the cleanest fix touches git-sync too.** Here's the honest tradeoff.

The fundamental tension: with git-sync not attaching the sentinel, *something* has to detect the race. You can't have both "worker stays clean (pure `errors.Is`)" **and** "no git-sync change" — one of those has to give. Three ways to resolve it:

## Option 1 — Fix git-sync, re-vendor *(the correct owner; still effectively one PR)*
The defect is that git-sync's own API contract ("`Sync`/`Replicate` report a `*RefRejectedError` … satisfying `errors.Is(ErrTargetRefMoved)`") is simply false. Fix is one word in two functions (`push.go`):
```go
func asRefRejectedError(err error) error {
    var cs packp.CommandStatusErr        // was *packp.CommandStatusErr
    if !errors.As(err, &cs) { return err }
    return &RefRejectedError{Ref: cs.ReferenceName.String(), Reason: cs.Status, moved: isConcurrentMove(cs.Status), err: err}
}
```
(same one-word change in `annotateLeaseFailure`, which is silently broken the same way). Then add a git-sync test driving a real `report.Error()`, bump your pseudo-version pin, `go mod vendor`. **The re-vendor diff lands in this same mirror-pipeline PR**, the worker stays exactly as written, and you also fix the lease-hint annotation for every git-sync consumer. You already pin a main-commit pseudo-version, so you control this — it's a 1-line commit on a repo you own.

## Option 2 — Worker-side detection, fully contained, zero git-sync change
Stop relying on the never-attached sentinel. I verified **both** of these work through the real prod wrap chain:
```go
func isConcurrentRefError(err error) bool {
    if errors.Is(err, gitsync.ErrTargetRefMoved) { return true } // lights up free once git-sync is fixed
    var cs packp.CommandStatusErr                                // go-git returns it by value
    if errors.As(err, &cs) {
        return strings.Contains(strings.ToLower(cs.Status), "remote ref has changed")
    }
    return false
}
```
Works in prod today, survives `go mod vendor`. **Cost:** it reaches past git-sync into go-git's `packp` and re-introduces worker-side reason matching — i.e. it walks back exactly what commits 2–3 did on purpose. (The even-simpler variant is just substring-matching `err.Error()` — that's literally your commit 1, which *worked*; commits 2–3 "improved" it into being inert.)

## Option 3 — Hand-edit `vendor/.../push.go` *(don't)*
One line, worker stays clean, and your CI wouldn't catch it (no vendor-sync check, gofmt skips vendor). But the next `go mod vendor` anyone runs silently reverts it — a regression landmine. Only viable paired with landing it upstream, at which point you've done Option 1 anyway.

My recommendation is **Option 1**: it's the right owner, keeps the design you deliberately chose, and is barely more work than Option 2 since you control git-sync. Option 2 is the answer only if cutting a git-sync commit right now is a real blocker for you.

